President Biden has announced his intent to appoint several individuals to key roles in the Council of the Administrative Conference of the United States (ACUS), the National Capital Planning Commission (NCPC), and the President's Intelligence Advisory Board. The ACUS is an independent federal agency that works to improve administrative processes and procedures. The appointees to the ACUS include Kristen Clarke, Assistant Attorney General for Civil Rights; Fernando Raul Laguarda, General Counsel at AmeriCorps; Anne Joseph O'Connell, a law professor at Stanford University; and Jonathan Su, former Deputy Counsel to the President. The NCPC is responsible for planning and development in the National Capital Region, and the appointees to the Commission are Bryan Clark Green, an architecture expert and author, and Elizabeth M. Hewlett, an attorney and former Chairman of the Prince George's County Planning Board. Finally, Anne M. Finucane, the former Vice Chairman of Bank of America, will be appointed to the President's Intelligence Advisory Board, which provides independent advice on the effectiveness of the Intelligence Community.